708296f-b.title: Manhattan: 5th Avenue - Washington Mews
708296f-b.text:
Fifth Avenue, east side, north from the
Washington Mews (right of No. 1) and across
East 8th Street.
The apartment structure, No. 1 Fifth Avenue,
occupying the Avenue frontage between the above
two points is at the right and only partially
appears. Opposite same is the 5-story Hotel
Brevoort. This is at the N.E. corner of 8th Street.
Above East 9th Street begins the uniform utilitarian
apartment dwellings, identified with New York.
February 24, 1933
Views 11, 2
P. L. Sperr

723973f-a.title: Manhattan: 5th Avenue - Washington Mews
723973f-a.text:
Fifth Avenue, east side, from Washington Mews
(left) to Washington Suuare (right), showing the
renrs of the buildings that face on the Park. These
are the holdings of the Sailors' Snug Harbor Corp.
and have an interesting background. Originally
intended for a home for retired seamen, they are
now rented to private individuals. The current
lack of response has caused the Corp. to come to
the conclusion that modern times demand modern
conveniences. Henovstions were therefore com-
pulsory in order to protect their equity.
Views 2 and 3 show details of this work.
Appearing in the latter, are the 2-story studio's
at the rear of the towering apartment building,
No. 1 Fifth Avenue. These are former stables
and front on the north side of the Mews, extend-
ing eastward to University Place.
View 1: March 29, 1933
Views 2, 3: May 10, 1939
P. L. Sperr
